concept_explanation.override_annotation:
When you write a method that REPLACES an inherited one, mark it with `@Override`:

```java
class Product {
    // ...

    @Override
    public String toString() {
        return "Product #" + id + " " + name;
    }
}
```

**What `@Override` does**:
- Tells the compiler: 'this should override an inherited method'
- If you misspell the method name or get the signature wrong, the compiler errors out
- Without `@Override`, you'd accidentally create a NEW method instead of overriding

**Example of the trap @Override prevents**:

```java
@Override
public boolean equals(Product other) {  // WRONG — parameter should be Object, not Product
    // ...
}
// Compiler error: 'method does not override or implement a method from a supertype'
```

Without `@Override`, this would compile — and silently fail to override `equals`. With `@Override`, the compiler catches the bug immediately.

**Convention**: use `@Override` EVERY time you override. Modern Java codebases require it.

concept_explanation.hashcode_method:
**`hashCode()`** returns an int that represents this object's 'identity' for hash-based collections (HashMap, HashSet — covered later).

**Why does it matter?** When you put objects in a HashMap or HashSet, Java uses their hashCode to find them quickly. If two equal objects have DIFFERENT hashCodes, the collection breaks — it can't find duplicates.

**The equals/hashCode contract** (Java's most famous rule):

> If `a.equals(b)` is true, then `a.hashCode() == b.hashCode()` MUST be true.

The reverse doesn't have to hold (different objects CAN have the same hashCode — called 'collisions' — they're acceptable). But equal objects MUST have equal hashCodes.

**Consequence**: if you override `equals`, you MUST also override `hashCode`. Failing to do so means your class is broken when used with HashMap/HashSet/HashTable — even though the code still 'compiles and runs.'

**Overriding hashCode using Objects.hash**:
```java
@Override
public int hashCode() {
    return Objects.hash(id);  // hash based on whatever equals uses
}
```

If equals uses multiple fields:
```java
@Override
public int hashCode() {
    return Objects.hash(id, name, stock, price);
}
```

`Objects.hash(...)` is a helper that combines multiple values into a single hash. Easy and correct.

**Critical rule**: ALWAYS use the SAME FIELDS in `hashCode` that you use in `equals`. If equals compares (id, name), hashCode uses (id, name). Same set of fields.

concept_explanation.complete_pattern:
**Putting it all together — a complete value class**:

```java
import java.util.Objects;

class Product {
    private final int id;
    private final String name;
    private final double price;

    public Product(int id, String name, double price) {
        this.id = id;
        this.name = name;
        this.price = price;
    }

    public int getId() { return id; }
    public String getName() { return name; }
    public double getPrice() { return price; }

    @Override
    public String toString() {
        return "Product[id=" + id + ", name=" + name + ", price=" + price + "]";
    }

    @Override
    public boolean equals(Object other) {
        if (this == other) return true;
        if (!(other instanceof Product)) return false;
        Product p = (Product) other;
        return this.id == p.id
            && Objects.equals(this.name, p.name)
            && Double.compare(this.price, p.price) == 0;
    }

    @Override
    public int hashCode() {
        return Objects.hash(id, name, price);
    }
}
```

This is THE template for value classes in Java. Memorize the pattern.

**Most IDEs auto-generate this**: in IntelliJ, press Alt+Insert → 'equals() and hashCode()' → pick fields. IDE generates correct code following this exact template. But you should know what's being generated and why.

step_by_step_solution.details:
```java
@Override
public String toString() {
    return "Product[#" + id + " " + name + " — Stock: " + stock + ", Price: ₹" + price + "]";
}
```

Four fields shown clearly. The `@Override` annotation tells the compiler 'this replaces the inherited toString.' If we accidentally wrote `toStrng()` (typo), the compiler would error: 'doesn't override anything.'

With this method, `System.out.println(product)` now produces:
`Product[#101 Wireless Mouse — Stock: 45, Price: ₹599.99]`

Much better than the default garbage.

```java
@Override
public boolean equals(Object other) {
    if (this == other) return true;
    if (!(other instanceof Product)) return false;
    Product p = (Product) other;
    return this.id == p.id;
}
```

Follow the template exactly:
1. Same reference? Yes, equal.
2. Different type (or null)? No, not equal.
3. Cast and compare.

**Why compare only by id?** This is a design decision. For entities (database-backed objects), TWO Products with the same id are 'the same product' — possibly the same row in the database, perhaps fetched at different times. The name or price might have been updated, but the entity identity is the id.

For value objects (Money, Date, Point), you'd compare ALL fields. The choice depends on your class's semantics.

```java
@Override
public int hashCode() {
    return Objects.hash(id);
}
```

Since equals uses ONLY id, hashCode uses ONLY id. **This is the contract**: same fields in both methods.

**Why not just `return id;`?** That would also work for an int field (id IS already an int). But using `Objects.hash(id)` is consistent — if you ever add more fields to the comparison, it scales: `Objects.hash(id, name)`. Less likely to be forgotten.

Don't forget the `import java.util.Objects;` at the top of the file.

worked_example.final_code:
import java.util.Objects;

class Product {
    private final int id;
    private String name;
    private int stock;
    private double price;

    public Product(int id, String name, int stock, double price) {
        if (id <= 0) throw new IllegalArgumentException("ID must be positive");
        if (name == null || name.isBlank()) throw new IllegalArgumentException("Name required");
        if (stock < 0) throw new IllegalArgumentException("Stock cannot be negative");
        if (price < 0) throw new IllegalArgumentException("Price cannot be negative");
        this.id = id;
        this.name = name;
        this.stock = stock;
        this.price = price;
    }

    public int getId() { return id; }
    public String getName() { return name; }
    public int getStock() { return stock; }
    public double getPrice() { return price; }

    @Override
    public String toString() {
        return "Product[#" + id + " " + name + " — Stock: " + stock + ", Price: ₹" + price + "]";
    }

    @Override
    public boolean equals(Object other) {
        if (this == other) return true;
        if (!(other instanceof Product)) return false;
        Product p = (Product) other;
        return this.id == p.id;
    }

    @Override
    public int hashCode() {
        return Objects.hash(id);
    }
}

public class ProductV4 {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Product p1 = new Product(101, "Mouse", 45, 599.99);
        Product p2 = new Product(101, "Wireless Mouse", 50, 549.99);
        Product p3 = new Product(102, "Mouse", 45, 599.99);

        System.out.println("=== toString ===");
        System.out.println(p1);
        System.out.println("As string: " + p1);

        System.out.println("\n=== equals ===");
        System.out.println("p1 == p2: " + (p1 == p2));
        System.out.println("p1.equals(p2): " + p1.equals(p2));
        System.out.println("p1.equals(p3): " + p1.equals(p3));
        System.out.println("p1.equals(null): " + p1.equals(null));
        System.out.println("p1.equals(\"hello\"): " + p1.equals("hello"));

        System.out.println("\n=== hashCode contract ===");
        System.out.println("p1.equals(p2): " + p1.equals(p2));
        System.out.println("p1.hashCode() == p2.hashCode(): " + (p1.hashCode() == p2.hashCode()));
    }
}

